    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Dagger: transpose of a matrix (classical analogue)
; For quantum: conjugate transpose of the channel

(define (transpose mat)
  (apply map list mat))

(define channel '((0.7 0.3) (0.2 0.8)))
(define dagger (transpose channel))

(display "channel:  ") (display channel) (newline)
(display "dagger:   ") (display dagger) (newline)
; In the quantum case, dagger is the unique
; adjoint with respect to the Hilbert-Schmidt
; inner product. Bayesian inversion is a special case.
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Dagger = transpose (classical), conjugate transpose (quantum)
import numpy as np

channel = np.array([[0.7, 0.3], [0.2, 0.8]])
dagger = channel.T

print(f"channel:\\n{channel}")
print(f"dagger (transpose):\\n{dagger}")
`} />
    </div>

    <h3>Bayesian inversion from the dagger</h3>
    <p>Given a prior state π and a channel f, the Bayesian inverse f†_π is the unique channel such that the joint distribution factors correctly: π ⊗ f = f†_π ⊗ (f applied to π). In the quantum case, this is <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petz_recovery_map"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Petz recovery</a>.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Bayesian inversion via dagger and prior
; f†_π(b) = Bayes' rule with prior π

(define (bayes-inverse channel prior)
  ; For a 2x2 classical channel:
  ; f†_π(j|i) = f(i|j) * π(j) / Σ_k f(i|k) * π(k)
  (let* ((n (length prior))
         (marginal (map (lambda (row)
           (apply + (map * row prior)))
           channel)))
    (let build-rows ((i 0) (rows '()))
      (if (= i n) (reverse rows)
        (build-rows (+ i 1)
          (cons
            (let build-cols ((j 0) (cols '()))
              (if (= j n) (reverse cols)
                (build-cols (+ j 1)
                  (cons
                    (let ((f-ij (list-ref (list-ref channel i) j))
                          (pi-j (list-ref prior j))
                          (marg-i (list-ref marginal i)))
                      (if (> marg-i 0)
                        (/ (* f-ij pi-j) marg-i)
                        0))
                    cols))))
            rows))))))

(define channel '((0.9 0.1) (0.2 0.8)))
(define prior '(0.3 0.7))
(define inv (bayes-inverse channel prior))

(display "channel: ") (display channel) (newline)
(display "prior: ") (display prior) (newline)
(display "Bayes inverse: ") (display inv)
`} />

    <h3>No-broadcasting theorem</h3>
    <p>Classical distributions can be copied (broadcast to multiple receivers without distortion). Quantum states cannot: the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/No-broadcasting_theorem"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>no-broadcasting theorem</a>. In Fritz's framework, copy detects determinism. In the quantum version, copy doesn't exist for non-commutative states. That's quantum weirdness showing up as missing structure.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Classical: copy works — broadcast a distribution
(define (copy-classical dist)
  ; (p, q) -> joint where both marginals equal (p, q)
  (let ((n (length dist)))
    (let build-rows ((i 0) (rows '()))
      (if (= i n) (reverse rows)
        (build-rows (+ i 1)
          (cons
            (let build-cols ((j 0) (cols '()))
              (if (= j n) (reverse cols)
                (build-cols (+ j 1)
                  (cons (if (= i j) (list-ref dist i) 0) cols))))
            rows))))))

(define dist '(0.3 0.7))
(define copied (copy-classical dist))

(display "original: ") (display dist) (newline)
(display "copied (joint): ") (display copied) (newline)
(display "marginal 1: ")
(display (map (lambda (row) (apply + row)) copied)) (newline)
; Both marginals equal the original.
; Quantum: this construction FAILS for non-diagonal
; density matrices. No copy = no broadcasting.
`} />

